{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653923"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:49:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:49:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18598"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18598"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0,0.26,0.11,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11330"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76073"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11330"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18598"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61574"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10570"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26257"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76073"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe bulbourethral glands are accessory sex glands in the male reproductive system that contribute to the composition of semen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of bulbourethral glands?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Synthesises prostaglandins for sperm motility","Produces testosterone for male sexual function","Produces fructose for sperm nutrition","Secretes proteolytic enzymes for semen liquefaction","Produces alkaline mucoid secretions for urethral lubrication"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eproduction of alkaline mucoid secretions for urethral lubrication\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of bulbourethral glands. These glands secrete a clear, slippery fluid during sexual arousal that helps neutralise any acidic residue in the urethra and provides lubrication for sperm transport.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynthesis of prostaglandins for sperm motility\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily a function of the seminal vesicles\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of fructose for sperm nutrition\u003C/strong\u003E - Fructose is produced by the seminal vesicles, not the bulbourethral glands\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecretion of proteolytic enzymes for semen liquefaction\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a function of the prostate gland\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of testosterone for male sexual function\u003C/strong\u003E - Testosterone is produced by the Leydig cells in the testes\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe alkaline nature of bulbourethral gland secretions is particularly important as it helps neutralise the acidic environment of the urethra, which could otherwise damage sperm cells during ejaculation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bulbourethral glands secrete a clear mucoid fluid during sexual arousal that helps lubricate and neutralise urethral acidity.","Also known as Cowper glands, bulbourethral glands are paired structures located inferior to the prostate gland.","The alkaline secretions from bulbourethral glands help create an optimal environment for sperm survival."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61574"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18598"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61574"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T23:46:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T23:47:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11330"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76073"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4934"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Reproductive System (Male)","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T12:54